	id="Expla_Dilation">
	<title>The Dilation Transformations</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>The dilation transformations of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> are given by</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>D\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[n],\quad D(\Vect{x}) := s\cdot\Vect{x}</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			<para>where <latex><![CDATA[ s > 1 ]]></latex> is a fixed number. Thus <latex>D</latex> magnifies or dilates each vector and, therefore, each object in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> by the factor <latex>s</latex> &ndash; hence the name &lsquo;dilation transformation&rsquo;.</para>
			
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/Dilation.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
				<caption>A dilation of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> with dilation factor <latex>3/2</latex>.</caption>
			</figure>
		</block>
		
		<block>
			<para>To find the matrix representing <latex>D</latex>, we note that <latex>D</latex> transforms the basic vector <latex>\StdBss{j}</latex> into
				<index.glossary>
					<term>matrix</term><term>of a dilation</term>
					<info><para>The matrix representing the dilation of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> with factor <latex><![CDATA[ s > 1 ]]></latex> is represented by the matrix <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>; i.e. <latex>s</latex> times the identity matrix of size <latex>(n,n)</latex>.</para></info>
				</index.glossary>
				<index.glossary>
					<term>dilation</term><term>matrix</term>
					<info><para>The matrix representing the dilation of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> with factor <latex><![CDATA[ s > 1 ]]></latex> is represented by the matrix <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>; i.e. <latex>s</latex> times the identity matrix of size <latex>(n,n)</latex>.</para></info>
				</index.glossary>
			</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>D(\StdBss{j}) = s\cdot \StdBss{j} = (0,\dots ,0,s,0,\dots ,0)</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			<para>Therefore <latex>D</latex> is represented by the matrix of size <latex>(n,n)</latex></para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
s\cdot \IdMtrx[n] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{cccc}
s & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\
0 & s &             & 0 \\
\vdots & & \ddots & \vdots \\
0 & 0 & \cdots & s
\end{array}
\right]
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			<para>For example, the dilation of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> in the picture above is</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
D\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2],\qquad D(x,y)=\tfrac{3}{2}\cdot (x,y) = 
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
\tfrac{3}{2} & 0 \\
0 & \tfrac{3}{2}
\end{array}
\right] \left[ \begin{array}{c} x \\ y \end{array} \right]
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>